    "body": "Hi maintainers — sharing a small third-party static architecture audit in case it is useful. Please feel free to close if this is not a useful tracking item for AutoGen.\n\nI ran [`agchk`](https://github.com/huangrichao2020/agchk) against the current `microsoft/autogen` repository with the personal-development profile:\n\n```bash\nagchk /tmp/agchk-outreach/autogen --profile personal\n```\n\nThis is not a vulnerability disclosure. It is a static architecture-level scan intended to identify agent-runtime complexity patterns and possible documentation/rubric improvements.\n\n## Summary\n\n- Architecture era: `铁器时代` / Iron Age, `47/100`\n- Share line: `这个 Agent 项目处于 铁器时代（47/100）：具备较清晰的工具、记忆和技能分层，开始可维护。`\n- Overall health signal: `unstable`\n- Finding counts: `critical=0`, `high=6`, `medium=15`, `low=65`\n\n## Signals that looked most useful\n\n1. **Runtime/orchestration complexity**\n   AutoGen naturally contains many orchestration concepts. The scan suggests it may be valuable to keep a concise architecture map for which layer owns routing, scheduling, recovery, memory/session boundaries, and tool execution.\n\n2. **Completion closure in generated/docs workflows**\n   Some docs/scripts look like they create or update artifacts without an explicit reusable closure model. A review rubric like `artifact created -> indexed -> discoverable -> reusable -> accepted` may help agent-generated contributions stay maintainable.\n\n3. **Memory/session freshness boundaries**\n   The scan saw many memory-like examples and samples. A short guide distinguishing hot context, session state, persisted state, and long-term memory could make the mental model easier for new users.\n\n4. **Code execution findings need context**\n   Some `exec` findings are intentional or already acknowledged in validation/security-related code. The useful follow-up is probably not “remove exec everywhere”, but “make trust boundaries and intended execution contexts unmistakable.”\n\n## Likely false positives / caveats\n\n- SQLModel-style `session.exec(...)` is not Python `exec` and should be ignored by generic scanners.\n- Some execution-related findings are in docs, tests, validation, or explicitly security-aware code.\n- Large multi-language repos amplify static pattern counts, so the score is best read as an architecture-complexity signal.\n\n## Why I am filing this\n\nThe goal is to share a compact external view, not to ask AutoGen to adopt another tool. If any signal is useful, I can follow up with a narrowly scoped docs proposal. Separately, AutoGen is a strong regression target for improving agchk false-positive handling around `session.exec`, provider implementations, and multi-runtime repos.\n\nRelated themes I noticed while searching existing issues: #6017, #7230, #7405, and #7613.\n",
